`Field#getElementType()` differs under GWT when faced with wildcards; on the desktop it returns `null`, under GWT it returns a non-null value (probably `java.lang.Object.class`). Example which passes under desktop but fails when ported to GWT:

``` java
public class ElementTypeTest {
    List<? extends Object> wildcardField0;
    List<? super Object> wildcardField1;
    List<?> wildcardField2;

    @Test
    public void testFieldElementType() throws ReflectionException {
        assertNull(ClassReflection.getDeclaredField(getClass(), "wildcardField0").getElementType(0));
        assertNull(ClassReflection.getDeclaredField(getClass(), "wildcardField1").getElementType(0));
        assertNull(ClassReflection.getDeclaredField(getClass(), "wildcardField2").getElementType(0));
    }
}
```

I think the correct behavior is to return `null` for a wildcard type.

